##### 3.

Condiser other datasets.

now have a look into Government Response Index Tracker collected by Oxford University, the interpretation of the variables is here

The variables chosen shows below with definition and coding, each measured in ordinal scale.

Variable name Variable definition Variable coding
*C2_Workplace closing Record closings of workplaces 0 - no measures, 1 - recommend closing (or recommend work from home), 2 - require closing (or work from home) for some sectors or categories of workers, 3 - require closing (or work from home) for all-but-essential workplaces (eg grocery stores, doctors), Blank - no data
*C6_Stay at home requirements Record orders to ‘shelter-in-place’ and otherwise confine to the home 0 - no measures, 1 - recommend not leaving house, 2 - require not leaving house with exceptions for daily exercise, grocery shopping, and ‘essential’ trips, 3 - require not leaving house with minimal exceptions (eg allowed to leave once a week, or only one person can leave at a time, etc), Blank - no data

Brazil.

1.Activity change in retail and recreation places related to level of staying at home requirements.

2.Activity change in frequency that people visiting the residencial places, given level of requirements on staying at home.

#### By the plot below, we observe that public reaction after different level of closing workplaces. The frequency of visiting workplaces sharply decreased after government required closing(or work from home) for all-but-essential workplaces (eg grocery stores, doctors). But in the mid-late people tend to visiting workplaces under level 3 closing policy.
